<article>
    <h1>DAINTY DESSERTS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201213/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-13"><time>2020-12-13</time></a>
        - <span>FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Dessert ta­bles are likely to be less lav­ish this year, with smaller cakes and other sweet treats.</p>
    <p>French bak­ery-restau­rant Paul Sin­ga­pore of­fers two sizes for its log cakes – good for about four peo­ple, or if you want to mix and match flavours – and prices start at $30. Op­tions in­clude a cit­ron meringue log cake and choco­late pear bavaroise log cake.</p>
    <p>Add on an or­der of mini mont blanc tart ($39 for eight pieces) or mini berries tart ($36 for eight pieces).</p>
    <p>Over at Re­gent Sin­ga­pore, its log cakes come in three sizes: in­di­vid­ual slices, medium (500g) and large (1kg). The cakes make good gifts and pair well with cock­tails from its Man­hat­tan bar, which come in bot­tle sizes rang­ing from 100ml to 700ml.</p>
    <p>Or opt for af­ter­noon tea sets that come in handy three-tier pack­ages from Re­gent’s Tea Lounge, which in­clude sweet and savoury pas­tries and cakes.</p>
    <p>Hol­i­day Inn Sin­ga­pore Or­chard City Cen­tre of­fers af­ter­noon tea sets for take­away, with one just for chil­dren.</p>
    <p>On the menu are sand­wiches, pas­tries and a choco­late brownie and dough­nut topped with M&M’s.</p>

